<div class="title-block"><h3> THE FIRST NATION</h3></div>
<div class="expanded-content">
<p>                                
The Long Plain First Nation (LPFN) reserve is called Ga-Ke-Nush-Koo-De-Ag amongst the Ojibway Tribes of southern Manitoba. The word Ga-Ke-Nush-Koo-De-Ag in the Ojibway languagemeans "long plain" and refers to the geography of the lands. The lands are situated above and along the west bank of the Assiniboine River. </p>

<p>
Our Ojibway ancestors favoured the long natural open plains of the area. Oral history past down from our ancestors to elders tells the importance of the plains. Our people preferred this area for many reasons: <strong>camping and staging area, organic farming, strategic hunting area for wildlife and bison, and a natural lookout point. </strong>
</p>



 <div id="openDiv1"  style="display:none;" >
 <p>
Our ancestors hunted mainly Bison which was the main source of food. Bison were also hunted for their thick fur and hide which were traditionally processed to make clothing and the bones were made into tools. The area also provides other sources of food like elk, deer and rabbits. The area was on the path of the central flyway of the waterfowl which our people hunted every spring and fall. </p>
<p>
The Assiniboine River flows along the eastern banks of the reserve. Our people depended on the river for another food source setting nets for fishlike sturgeon and walleye. They hunted smaller mammals such beaver, muskrats and mink to make clothing. The tall white popular trees along the Assiniboine River were close to plains. These tall trees were used for building log homes in the winter. </p>
<p>
After Treaty No. 1 was signed, Long Plain became reserve land or Crown lands, which were controlled and managed by Indigenous and Northern Affairs Canada representatives, however in the last few decades; the First Nation has gradually taken control and manages of the lands. Management of our lands has led to land improvement and agricultural leasing. </p>
<p>
Long Plain First Nation reserve has no land use plan and land use planning to date has been on a project to project basis with only specific project site plans. The First Nation Government has identified the need for a land use plan and planning process that will enhance future economic development and land management. </p>
</div>

