<div class="title-block" style="float:left; width:100%;">
<h3>2.	BACKGROUND</h3>
</div>
<div class="expanded-content">
<p>
The main reserve is called Long Plain Reserve No. 6. It is located 14 km southwest of Portage La Prairie, Manitoba and 98 kilometers west of Winnipeg and 10 kilometers south off of Highway No. 1 and 16, and on Highway No. 305. The southeast boundary of the reserve runs along the west bank of the Assiniboine River and extends north and west from the river. </p>
<p>
In 1980, the LPFN Council successfully negotiated 45 acres of available federal surplus land from Canada as part of Bands Treaty Land Entitlement claim. The property became reserve in August 1981. The surplus lands are located adjacent to the City of Portage la Prairie.  The site was home to the Portage Indian Residential School for over hundred years and in 1982 the former residential school building was transformed into the Yellow quill College Inc. The college provided training and education to surrounding First Nations for over 10 years. The property is now called "Keeshkeemaquah Reserve", named after the last LPFN hereditary Chief.   </p>

 <div id="openDiv3"  style="display:none;" >
<p>
In 2004, on behalf of the First Nation, LPFN Trust purchased 2.81 acres of prime property from Manitoba Hydro located at 480 Madison Street in the City of Winnipeg, Manitoba. The land acquisition came with the former Manitoba Hydro maintenance building which has since been renovated and converted into an education facility. The property received pre-designation for leasing on July 12, 2012. The property became Long Plain Madison Indian Reserve No. 1 on May 14, 2013 with reserve status. This 2.81 acre property in is the planning stages of development.</p>


<p>
As of July 15, 2016, the First Nation owns 16,535.8acres of land equal or 25.83 square miles of lands; 12,755.8 acres or 19.93 square miles has Reserve or Crown status; 3,780 acres is presently in the process of land conversion to reserve status.The majority of the First Nation lands are used for agriculture. The remaining lands are used for community development and natural areas. </p>
</div>

