<div class="title-block" style="float:left; width:100%;">
<h3>5.	GUIDING PRINCIPLES</h3>
</div>
<div class="expanded-content">
<p>
Based on our First Nation philosophy, religion, history, traditions, culture, experiences, the following principles shall be used in the planning process:</p>

<ul class="content-listing">
<li> - Our people believed our ancestors were placed on the earth; and universe, the sky and lands were made by the creator; </li>
<li> - That every natural object and living being has spirit, meaning, and purpose;</li>
<li> - That the natural world be respected and preserved for future generations;</li>
<li> - That we shall always give thanks to our creator for the use of lands;</li>
<li> - That we keep in mind our ancestors have occupied and lived on the lands what is now called Manitoba;</li>
<li> - That the lands acquired and occupied by our ancestors were considered to be our homelands;</li>
<li> - That we respect our traditions and ceremonies areas in the future planning process;</li>
<li> - That we respect and consider the natural state of the land and wildlife; </li>
<li> - That we designate land for potential economic and community developments areas;</li>
<li> - That we building awareness and capacity development with the Tribal Administration and community members;</li>
<li> - That we can manage our lands and property in a sustainable way;</li>
<li> - That we assess and analyze the socio-economic needs and requirements of community to ensure appropriate plans are made for future development; and,</li>
<li> - That we adopt modern planning strategies, technologies and concepts such as GIS and GPS mapping and zoning) for the land use plan. </li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="title-block" style="float:left; width:100%;">
<h3>6.	LAND USE POLICY</h3>
</div>
<div class="expanded-content">
<p>
The Long Plain First Nation (LPFN) Government recognizes that land use policies are required to regulate future land use and new development. They also recognize that there are legal, environmental, physical and spiritual aspects of the land need to be respected and considered. Future use of lands for residential, economic, education, recreation, health or infrastructure must follow the traditional protocol for the use of land.  </p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.1 Residential Development</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government (FN) recognizes that adequate, safe and efficient housing is necessary for all members residing on First Nation lands. Lands shall be designated for future housing development sites. The FN Government shall designate future residential development areas with specific subzones, subdivision, lots, numbers, types and sizes; </p>

 <div id="openDiv6"  style="display:none;" >
<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.2 Economic Development</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government (FN) recognizes economic development is necessary to establish a sustainable local economy; provide business support services, encourage small business, develop business and commercial ventures both on the main reserve and on the urban reserve properties. Lands shall be zoned or designated for economic development areas, agricultural lands, industrial and commercial development and tourism areas. Urban reserve properties such as the Long Plain Madison Indian Reserve No. 1 and Long Plain Reserve No. 6 (Keeshkeemaquah Reserve) have been designated for commercial development and leasing and is requires an official development plan;</p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.3 Education</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government recognizes that education is our future well-being, economic and social development. Education is the basis of building a strong community. Planning for new education facilities are required to meet the future education needs of the growing on-reserve population. Lands for educational purposes shall be designated or zoned for educational purposes. </p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.4 Recreation</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government recognizes that promoting recreational programs and activities in the community increases well-being and healthy lifestyles for our members. Lands shall be identified and set aside for present and future recreational purposes that will enhance the quality of life of our members;</p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.5Health</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government recognizes that a healthy environment, lifestyles and health support services nurtures the physical, mental and spiritual well-being of the community. The FN Government shall develop new health program, services, and facilities for the increasing population of the community. They shall designate lands for future health related developments and facilities such as Elders Health Care Facility, Palliative Care Centre, Retirement Home Complex, Emergency Care Centre and Drug and Alcohol Prevention and Treatment Centre.  </p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.6 Infrastructure</h3></div>

<p>the First Nation Government recognizes that to support socio-economic development in our community, appropriate infrastructure is required. Transportation routes, water and sewer services, drainage systems, electrical and communications systems are required to support future development. Lands required for future infrastructure systems shall be designated. Lands shall be surveyed and mapped with Geographic Information System and Global Positioning System technology. </p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.7 Ceremonial and Cultural Areas</h3></div>

<p> the First Nation Government recognizes that our ceremonial and cultural areas are special to our community. The First Nation people have a special relationship with our lands and territory. In the past, our ancestors used the specific land areas for ceremonial and cultural purposes. These lands shall be identified, preserved and protected by land designation. </p>

<div class="fancy-title title-border" style="float:left; width:100%;"><h3>6.8Natural Areas</h3></div>

<p> the First Nation Government recognizes that as First Nations, the Creator has given our people a religion based on the natural world, and that all living species and natural resources are connected spiritually, that we must share the lands with wildlife, waterfowl and other living animal species. We must identify and preserve the natural environment from encroachment. </p>
</div>

